[[File:Hequet-self portrait.jpg|thumb|185px|Self-portrait (c.1890)]] [[File:Hequet-Military.jpg|thumb|185px|Military Type]] '''Juan Bautista Diógenes Hequet''', or '''Hecquet''' (26 September 1866, [[Montevideo]] - 28 August 1902, Montevideo) was an Uruguayan painter, graphic artist and professor, best known for his [[Military art|battle scenes]].
== Biography == His first art lessons were in the workshop of his father, the French-born [[lithographer]], José Adolfo Hequet (1826-1888). In 1886, he went to Paris to perfect his etching techniques with {{ill|Louis Tauzin|fr}}. Two years later, he enrolled at the municipal art school in the [[14th arrondissement of Paris|14th arrondissement]], operated by {{ill|Auguste Truphème|fr|Auguste Truphème (peintre)}}.<ref name="P">[http://www.portondesanpedro.com/autor-curriculum.php?id=437 Brief biography] @ Porton de san Pedro.</ref> It was there that he first became interested in military art and was influenced by the works of [[Jean-Louis-Ernest Meissonier|Meissonier]], [[Alphonse-Marie-Adolphe de Neuville|Neuville]] and [[Édouard Detaille|Detaille]].<ref>[http://www.grumete.com.uy/ayuda/biografia.asp?identificador=149&categoria=646 Biographical notes] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603131203/http://www.grumete.com.uy/ayuda/biografia.asp?identificador=149&categoria=646 |date=June 3, 2015 }} @ Grumete.</ref>
Upon returning to Montevideo, he set about producing a large number of historical works. Outstanding among these was a series called "Episodios Nacionales", that depicted all of the principal events in the history of Uruguay, including the "[[Cry of Asencio]]" and the "[[Battle of Las Piedras (1811)|Battle of Las Piedras]]".<ref>[http://www.museohistorico.gub.uy/innovaportal/v/64519/33/mecweb/diogenes-hequet?contid=42669 Biographical notes] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150603130550/http://www.museohistorico.gub.uy/innovaportal/v/64519/33/mecweb/diogenes-hequet?contid=42669 |date=June 3, 2015 }} @ the Museo Histórico.</ref> In addition to these works, he also created nativist works depicting peasant life and rural landscapes.
In 1893, he made an unsuccessful effort to establish a new school of fine arts. Later he joined with several other Uruguayan artists to create the "Artistic Circle of Uruguay". [[Juan Manuel Blanes]] was its first President.<ref name="P" />
Shortly after, he became a Professor at the [[University of the Republic (Uruguay)|University of the Republic]], where he held the chairs of drawing (in the "Sección Preparatoria") and ornament (in the "Facultad de Matemáticas"); positions he held until his death. He also provided illustrations for several magazines and newspapers.<ref name="P" />
