{{For|the building in Rome|Regia}} [[File:SantIvo_Drawing_06.jpg|right|thumb|Plan of [[Francesco Borromini]]'s ''Pallazzo della Sapienzao'' (1642-1660), originally the home of [[Sapienza University of Rome]]. As a place of authority, it is built according to the regia type.]] '''Regia''' is a classical building type: a place where a governing authority resides.<ref name=Cornell>{{cite book|last1=Cornell|first1=T.J.|title=The beginnings of Rome : Italy and Rome from the Bronze Age to the Punic Wars (c.1000 - 264 BC)|date=1995|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=9780415015967|pages=239–241|edition=Reprinted.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UgoOD2XDpzIC&pg=PA239|accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref><ref name="The Archaeology of Early Rome and Latium">{{cite book|last1=Holloway|first1=Ross|title=The Archaeology of Early Rome and Latium|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317761594|pages=62–3|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yqqOAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA62|accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref> It is among the ancient building types. Others are the tholos, the temple, the theater, the dwelling, and the shop. Buildings according to this type may be rectangular in plan with an interior courtyard.<ref>{{Citation | title = Architectural Principles In the Age of Historicism | page = 159 |publisher= Yale University Press | author= Robert Jan van Pelt & Carroll William Westfall | date = 1991 }}</ref>
